metadata.name: Orbit Traps #67
metadata.description:
This is my first foray into generative NFTs. This is a variation of the Mandelbrot set. I first built a tool in Unity to find and record interesting locations of the set. Then I real-time render these parts inside of a shader and apply different orbit traps to the fractal. There is quite a bit of variation. Apart from different parts, and zoom levels, of the set, there are different orbit traps, symmetries, colors and animations (rare). I tried to balance the variety of images with the visual quality. This is a trade off because the more variety you allow for, the more likely it is that some of them will not look ideal. 

In the unlikely event you mint a completely black or white image, drop me a mail at countfrolic@gmail.com and I'll gladly mint you a new one.

Yours,
Martijn Steinrucken
The Art of Code

metadata.name: Living Squares Study II #14
metadata.description:
1024x1024 generative animation (Vanilla JS canvas)

This piece is an evolving painting. Press "s" to download a png file on live.
In this world of rotating squares they try to find a place and interact with each other.
The squares can have a fixed number of divisions or can grow with size.
An optional feature generates lines in the background when they collide.
There are a much more other features.
Wait and see how the painting evolves, you can click or touch to toggle the animation.


12 features included

36 Color palettes
Number of squares (between 2 and 12)
Dashing pixels and linewidth
Stripe width (narrow, normal, thick)
Skew (true or false)
Number of square divisions
Rotation Speed
Rotation Direction
Opacity 
Background lines

Daniel Juli√†
December 2021

metadata.name: Fractal Flower #44
metadata.description:
In this series I continue my exploration of the Mandelbrot set. This iconic fractal can be tweaked and used to make many different organic looking effects. 

Rarity comes from the following modifiers:
- Star = 10%
- Web = 10%
- Guiding Star = 5%
- Shapeshifter = 5%
- Rippler = 2.5%

metadata.name: Pigments #70
metadata.description:
‚ÄúPigments‚Äù is a generative art project that explores the beauty of optical color blending and the power of noise. 

At the heart of this work is a random composition of rectangles that are made up of dots. These pigments are arranged in multiple layers, each layer using a different color from one of the carefully curated color palettes. Each palette consists of three to five colors. 

As the pigments are shifted by random noise, new hues and patterns emerge, creating a lovely display of color and movement.

In live mode:
- Press [1]-[5] to change the resolution.
- Press [s] to save a png file at the current resolution.

This is my first generative art project. Created with p5js.

________

Looks best on high-resolution screens and viewed in live mode. When displayed on a low-resolution screen, an unintended moir√© pattern may appear.

metadata.name: Bauhausstadt #90
metadata.description:
Bauhausstadt (Bauhaus City) is a series that draws direct inspiration from Ludwig Karl Hilberseimer's (September 14, 1885 ‚Äì May 6, 1967) work on city planning through a Bauhaus lens. Specifically, the series references his illustration from Bauhaus Magazine (Number 2, 1929) depicting a sustainable relationship between humans, industry, and nature. Hilberseimer proposed that this can be achieved through the construction of human habitation that ensures security for all people against disasters and crises.

This series explores Hilberseimer's use of "protective" architecture and repetition in his work, raising questions about the aesthetic and functional value of such an approach in urban planning. Through over 200 hand-drawn/coloured illustrations and a touch of randomness, the project visually poses this question and leaves it up to the viewer to decide its worth.

metadata.name: Sea of Monoliths #216
Hello World #225
metadata.description:
With this token, I am entering a new chapter in making generative art. 

I recorded myself saying "Hello World" and converted the sound file to a set of amplitudes extracted from my voice. That set of amplitudes was then used to create a rotating set of discs that are orbiting a "Sun". 

As the system is rotating, the details of a generative overlay can be seen more clearly. This overlay is also a sneak peak into my next artwork coming soon.

Press keys 1-4 to change the view, press "F" to toggle framerate between 60 and 30.
